
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `lsblk` baraye didan list-e block device-ha (mesl HDD, SSD, USB drives) dar system-e shoma be kar miravad. In dastoor etela'ati mesl name device, size, va mount point anha ra neshon midahad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `lsblk`     --> 💻 Namayesh device-haye block be soorate derakhti (tree)
    🔹 `lsblk -a`  --> 👀 Namayesh hameye device-ha, hata anha ke empty hastand.
    🔹 `lsblk -f`  --> 🗂️ Namayesh etela'at file system mesl UUID va LABEL.
    🔹 `lsblk -p`  --> 📍 Namayesh path-haye kamel device-ha.
    🔹 `lsblk -m`  --> 💾 Namayesh etela'at permission va ownership.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ lsblk

    🔹 Namayesh yek list az device-haye block ba etela'at asasi.

    $ lsblk -f

    🔹 Namayesh device-haye block ba etela'at file system.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ lsblk -a | grep sda

    🔹 Peyda kardan etela'at marboot be device "sda" az hame device ha.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `lsblk` command is used to list information about block devices (like HDD, SSD, USB drives) in your system. It displays information like device name, size, and mount point.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `lsblk`     --> 💻 Display block devices in a tree-like format.
    🔹 `lsblk -a`  --> 👀 Show all devices, including empty ones.
    🔹 `lsblk -f`  --> 🗂️ Display filesystem information such as UUID and LABEL.
    🔹 `lsblk -p`  --> 📍 Show full device paths.
    🔹 `lsblk -m`  --> 💾 Show permissions and ownership information.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ lsblk

    🔹 Displays a list of block devices with basic information.

    $ lsblk -f

    🔹 Displays block devices with filesystem information.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ lsblk -a | grep sda

    🔹 Find information about the "sda" device from all devices.

